column10:
I also submitted written testimony with the following comment:
Poverty and income inequality are associated with violence, especially assault and homicide. Evidence supports that this is a causal link. And direct income support has been found to reduce firearm violence. Inequality predicts homicides better than any other variable. GBI alleviates the social costs of poverty, one of which is violence. 

Because of many GBI pilots throughout the country (and throughout the world) including Tacoma’s GRIT program, King County’s GBI pilot, and the Perigee Fund GBI pilot we have evidence of the immense benefits of GBI:  improved health for recipients and their children; increased income, housing, and food security; increased employment; and reduced unplanned pregnancies, firearm violence, and addiction. 

Food, shelter, and health care are basic human needs. It is fundamentally unsafe for individuals to experience food insecurity, live unsheltered, or lack health care. GBI is the most efficient, cost effective way to directly address these basic needs.

An extensive 2022 report to the State Legislature outlines the feasibility of GBI in Washington State. GBI is not only feasible, it is necessary to tackle the widening income disparities in Washington and to protect the health and safety of Washington residents.
